'''Bruce Hawker''' is a political commentator and chairman and founder of Campaigns and Communications Group, former Chairman and founding member of [[Hawker Britton]] (along with David Britton) and Chief Strategist for the [[Australian Labor Party]] having been working in State and Federal Labor politics for over 20 years.<ref name="ABC1">{{cite web | url=http://www.abc.net.au/unleashed/bruce-hawker-38704.html | title=Bruce Hawker - The Drum Opinion (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) | publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] | accessdate=2011-04-22}}</ref><ref name="TA1">{{cite web | url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/national-affairs/labor-pr-guru-bruce-hawker-spins-off-to-new-campaign-venture/story-fn59niix-1225983446277 | title=Labor PR guru Bruce Hawker spins off to new campaign venture <nowiki>|</nowiki> The Australian | publisher=[[The Australian]] | date=2011-01-07 | accessdate=2011-04-22 | author=Kelly, Joe}}</ref> Hawker was the [[Chief of Staff]] to former [[New South Wales]] [[Premier of New South Wales|Premier]] [[Bob Carr]] a position he held for 14 years before resigning to establish Hawker Britton in April 1997.<ref name="ABC1" /><ref name="TA1" /><ref name="TDT1">{{cite web | url=http://www.hawkerbritton.com/images/heritage/HB%20establishement%20articles%20(Mar%2097)%201.pdf | title=Carr's top two advisers resign | publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=2011-04-22 | author=English, Ben}}</ref>

== Early life ==

In relation to Hawker's resignation, Bob Carr said, "After all nine years is a long time to spend in a political office."<ref name="TA2">{{cite web | url=http://www.hawkerbritton.com/images/heritage/HB%20establishement%20articles%20(Mar%2097)%202.pdf | title=Senior staffers quit Carr office | publisher=[[The Australian]] | accessdate=2011-04-22 | author=Nason, David}}</ref><ref name="TDT1" /> Hawker has a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from the [[University of Queensland]] and a Law degree from the [[University of New South Wales]].<ref name="HB1">{{cite web | url=http://www.hawkerbritton.com/BruceHawker/6/Overview.html | title=Hawker Britton - Government Relations, Government Lobbying, Lobbyists, Campaigns, Strategies Consultancy | accessdate=2011-04-22}}</ref>

In 1997, Hawker and Britton resigned from their positions as Chief of Staff and Chief of Communications, respectively, to start Hawker Britton. The company grew and now has over 6 Australian offices, an office in [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]] and 3 international offices in [[Washington, D.C.]], [[London]] and [[Shanghai]].<ref name="HB1"/> 

== Political work ==

Following the [[Australian federal elections, 2010|2010 Australian federal elections]], a hung parliament resulted. Hawker lead the negotiations with independents [[Tony Windsor]] and [[Rob Oakeshott]] which secured the incumbent government lead by [[Julia Gillard]] a second term.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.news.com.au/features/federal-election/idependents-to-discuss-cabinet-reform-with-labor-strategist-bruce-hawker/story-fn5taogy-1225910233959 | title=Independents to discuss Cabinet reform with Labor strategist Bruce Hawker <nowiki>|</nowiki> News.com.au | publisher=News.com.au | date=2010-08-26 | accessdate=2011-04-22}}</ref>

Hawker is a regular contributor to [[The Sydney Morning Herald]], [[Sky News]] and the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]].<ref name="ABC1" />

